[src:react-query/abortcontroller] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:react-query/abortcontroller] It’s been available across browsers since March 2019.
[src:react-query/abortcontroller] The **`AbortController`** interface represents a controller object that allows you to abort one or more Web requests as and when desired.
[src:react-query/abortcontroller] You can create a new `AbortController` object using the `AbortController()` constructor.
[src:react-query/abortcontroller] Communicating with an asynchronous operation is done using an `AbortSignal` object.
[src:react-query/abortcontroller] Creates a new `AbortController` object instance.
[src:react-query/abortcontroller] Returns an `AbortSignal` object instance, which can be used to communicate with, or to abort, an asynchronous operation.
[src:react-query/abortcontroller] Aborts an asynchronous operation before it has completed.
[src:react-query/abortcontroller] This is able to abort fetch requests, consumption of any response bodies, and streams.
[src:react-query/abortcontroller] See the `AbortSignal` page for usage examples.
[src:react-query/abortcontroller] You can find a full working example on GitHub; you can also see it running live.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] Ajax is not a technology, but rather a programming pattern.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] HTML and CSS can be used in combination to mark up and style information.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] The webpage can be modified by JavaScript to dynamically display (and allow the user to interact with) the new information.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] The built-in XMLHttpRequest object is used to execute Ajax on webpages, allowing websites to load content onto the screen without refreshing the page.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] In the early-to-mid 1990s, most websites were based on complete HTML pages.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] Each user action required a complete new page to be loaded from the server.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] This process was inefficient, as reflected by the user experience: all page content disappeared, then the new page appeared.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] Each time the browser reloaded a page because of a partial change, all the content had to be re-sent, even though only some of the information had changed.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] This placed additional load on the server and made bandwidth a limiting factor in performance.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] The foundations of AJAX originate back in 1996 with the introduction of JavaScript 1.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] Developers quickly discovered that any HTML element which accepted a "src" attribute could be used to fetch remote data.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] By changing the src of a hidden frame, a developer could fetch remote data, process or display it without a page refresh.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] The remote data could be a string, JavaScript code, XML or a partial HTML page generated on the server.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] The same could be done with `<img>` and `<embed>` tags, but many developers were alarmed at the concept of an executable GIF and preferred to use the hidden `<iframe>`.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] This technique was used for both Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer, the two main browsers at the time, until developers discovered the XMLHTTP server object (MSXML 1.0) was included in Internet Explorer 4.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] Browser detection was then used to either implement the hidden `<iframe>` in Netscape or use the XMLHTTP (MSXML 1.0) object in IE 4.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] In 1996, the iframe tag was introduced by Internet Explorer; like the object element, it can load a part of the web page asynchronously.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] In 1998, the Microsoft Outlook Web Access team developed the concept behind the XMLHttpRequest scripting object.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] It appeared as XMLHTTP in the second version of the MSXML library, which shipped with Internet Explorer 5.0 in March 1999.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] The functionality of the Windows XMLHTTP ActiveX control in IE 5 was later implemented by Mozilla Firefox, Safari, Opera, Google Chrome, and other browsers as the XMLHttpRequest JavaScript object.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] Microsoft adopted the native XMLHttpRequest model as of Internet Explorer 7.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] Support for the ActiveX version remained in Internet Explorer and on "Internet Explorer mode" in Microsoft Edge.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] The utility of these background HTTP requests and asynchronous Web technologies remained fairly obscure until it started appearing in large scale online applications such as Outlook Web Access (2000) and Oddpost (2002).
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] Google made a wide deployment of standards-compliant, cross browser Ajax with Gmail (2004) and Google Maps (2005).
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] In October 2004 Kayak.com's public beta release was among the first large-scale e-commerce uses of what their developers at that time called "the xml http thing".
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] This increased interest in Ajax among web program developers.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] The term *AJAX* was publicly used on 18 February 2005 by Jesse James Garrett in an article titled *Ajax: A New Approach to Web Applications*, based on techniques used on Google pages.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] On 5 April 2006, the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) released the first draft specification for the XMLHttpRequest object in an attempt to create an official Web standard.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] The latest draft of the XMLHttpRequest object was published on 6 October 2016, and the XMLHttpRequest specification is now a living standard.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] The term *Ajax* has come to represent a broad group of Web technologies that can be used to implement a Web application that communicates with a server in the background, without interfering with the current state of the page.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] Since then, however, there have been a number of developments in the technologies used in an Ajax application, and in the definition of the term Ajax itself.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] XML is no longer required for data interchange and, therefore, XSLT is no longer required for the manipulation of data.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) is often used as an alternative format for data interchange, although other formats such as preformatted HTML or plain text can also be used.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] A variety of popular JavaScript libraries, including jQuery, include abstractions to assist in executing Ajax requests.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] An example of a simple Ajax request using the GET method, written in JavaScript.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] Ajax offers several benefits that can significantly enhance web application performance and user experience.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] By reducing server traffic and improving speed, Ajax plays a crucial role in modern web development.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] One key advantage of Ajax is its capacity to render web applications without requiring data retrieval, resulting in reduced server traffic.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] This optimization minimizes response times on both the server and client sides, eliminating the need for users to endure loading screens.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] Furthermore, Ajax facilitates asynchronous processing by simplifying the utilization of XmlHttpRequest, which enables efficient handling of requests for asynchronous data retrieval.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] Additionally, the dynamic loading of content enhances the application's performance significantly.
[src:react-query/ajax-programming] Besides, Ajax enjoys broad support across all major web browsers, including Microsoft Internet Explorer versions 5 and above, Mozilla Firefox versions 1.0 and beyond, Opera versions 7.6 and above, and Apple Safari versions 1.2 and higher.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] The Fetch API provides an interface for fetching resources (including across the network).
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] It is a more powerful and flexible replacement for `XMLHttpRequest`.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] The Fetch API uses `Request` and `Response` objects (and other things involved with network requests), as well as related concepts such as CORS and the HTTP Origin header semantics.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] For making a request and fetching a resource, use the `fetch()` method.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] It is a global method in both `Window` and `Worker` contexts.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] This makes it available in pretty much any context you might want to fetch resources in.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] The `fetch()` method takes one mandatory argument, the path to the resource you want to fetch.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] It returns a `Promise` that resolves to the `Response` to that request — as soon as the server responds with headers — **even if the server response is an HTTP error status**.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] You can also optionally pass in an `init` options object as the second argument (see `Request`).
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] Once a `Response` is retrieved, there are a number of methods available to define what the body content is and how it should be handled.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] You can create a request and response directly using the `Request()` and `Response()` constructors, but it's uncommon to do this directly.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] Instead, these are more likely to be created as results of other API actions (for example, `FetchEvent.respondWith()` from service workers).
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] Find out more about using the Fetch API features in Using Fetch.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] The `fetchLater()` API enables a developer to request a *deferred fetch*, that can be sent after a specified period of time, or when the page is closed or navigated away from.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] The `fetch()` method used to fetch a resource.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] Represents the set of options that can be used to configure a deferred fetch request.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] Represents the result of requesting a deferred fetch.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] Represents response/request headers, allowing you to query them and take different actions depending on the results.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] Controls the top-level quota for the `fetchLater()` API.
[src:react-query/api-fetch-api] Controls the shared cross-origin subframe quota for the `fetchLater()` API.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] The Fetch API provides a JavaScript interface for making HTTP requests and processing the responses.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] Fetch is the modern replacement for `XMLHttpRequest`: unlike `XMLHttpRequest`, which uses callbacks, Fetch is promise-based and is integrated with features of the modern web such as service workers and Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS).
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] With the Fetch API, you make a request by calling `fetch()`, which is available as a global function in both `window` and `worker` contexts.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] You pass it a `Request` object or a string containing the URL to fetch, along with an optional argument to configure the request.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` function returns a `Promise` which is fulfilled with a `Response` object representing the server's response.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] You can then check the request status and extract the body of the response in various formats, including text and JSON, by calling the appropriate method on the response.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] We declare a string containing the URL and then call `fetch()`, passing the URL with no extra options.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` function will reject the promise on some errors, but not if the server responds with an error status like `404`: so we also check the response status and throw if it is not OK.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] Otherwise, we fetch the response body content as JSON by calling the `json()` method of `Response`, and log one of its values.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that like `fetch()` itself, `json()` is asynchronous, as are all the other methods to access the response body content.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the rest of this page we'll look in more detail at the different stages of this process.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] 2. optionally, an object containing options to configure the request.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this section we'll look at some of the most commonly-used options.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] To read about all the options that can be given, see the `fetch()` reference page.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the `mode` option is set to `no-cors`, then `method` must be one of `GET`, `POST` or `HEAD`.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] The request body is the payload of the request: it's the thing the client is sending to the server.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] You cannot include a body with `GET` requests, but it's useful for requests that send content to the server, such as `POST` or `PUT` requests.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] For example, if you want to upload a file to the server, you might make a `POST` request and include the file as the request body.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] Other objects are converted to strings using their `toString()` method.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] See Locked and disturbed streams for more information.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] Request headers give the server information about the request: for example, in a `POST` request, the `Content-Type` header tells the server the format of the request's body.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] To set request headers, assign them to the `headers` option.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] Compared to using plain objects, the `Headers` object provides some additional input sanitization.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] For example, it normalizes header names to lowercase, strips leading and trailing whitespace from header values, and prevents certain headers from being set.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] Many headers are set automatically by the browser and can't be set by a script: these are called Forbidden request headers.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the `mode` option is set to `no-cors`, then the set of permitted headers is further restricted.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] `GET` requests don't have a body, but you can still send data to the server by appending it to the URL as a query string.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is a common way to send form data to the server.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] Whether a request can be made cross-origin or not is determined by the value of the `RequestInit.mode` option.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] This may take one of three values: `cors`, `same-origin`, or `no-cors`.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] See the reference documentation for `RequestInit.mode` for more details.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the context of the Fetch API, a credential is an extra piece of data sent along with the request that the server may use to authenticate the user.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] By default, credentials are only included in same-origin requests.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that if a cookie's `SameSite` attribute is set to `Strict` or `Lax`, then the cookie will not be sent cross-site, even if `credentials` is set to `include`.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] Including credentials in cross-origin requests can make a site vulnerable to CSRF attacks, so even if `credentials` is set to `include`, the server must also agree to their inclusion by including the `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` header in its response.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] Additionally, in this situation the server must explicitly specify the client's origin in the `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` response header (that is, `*` is not allowed).
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `Request()` constructor takes the same arguments as `fetch()` itself.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] This means that instead of passing options into `fetch()`, you can pass the same options to the `Request()` constructor, and then pass that object to `fetch()`.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] To make a request cancelable, create an `AbortController`, and assign its `AbortSignal` to the request's `signal` property.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] To cancel the request, call the controller's `abort()` method.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` call will reject the promise with an `AbortError` exception.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the request is aborted after the `fetch()` call has been fulfilled but before the response body has been read, then attempting to read the response body will reject with an `AbortError` exception.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] As soon as the browser has received the response status and headers from the server (and potentially before the response body itself has been received), the promise returned by `fetch()` is fulfilled with a `Response` object.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] The promise returned by `fetch()` will reject on some errors, such as a network error or a bad scheme.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] However, if the server responds with an error like `404`, then `fetch()` fulfills with a `Response`, so we have to check the status before we can read the response body.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `Response.status` property tells us the numerical status code, and the `Response.ok` property returns `true` if the status is in the 200 range.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] Just like the request, the response has a `headers` property which is a `Headers` object, and this contains any response headers that are exposed to scripts, subject to the exclusions made based on the response type.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] These are all asynchronous methods, returning a `Promise` which will be fulfilled with the body content.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] The method will throw an exception if the response body is not in the appropriate format: for example, if you call `json()` on a response that can't be parsed as JSON.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] Request and response bodies are actually `ReadableStream` objects, and whenever you read them, you're streaming the content.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is good for memory efficiency, because the browser doesn't have to buffer the entire response in memory before the caller retrieves it using a method like `json()`.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] This also means that the caller can process the content incrementally as it is received.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] If we use `Response.text()`, as above, we must wait until the whole file has been received before we can process any of it.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this example, we iterate asynchronously over the stream, processing each chunk as it arrives.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that when you access the body directly like this, you get the raw bytes of the response and must transform it yourself.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this case we call `ReadableStream.pipeThrough()` to pipe the response through a `TextDecoderStream`, which decodes the UTF-8-encoded body data as text.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the example below, we fetch a text resource and process it line by line, using a regular expression to look for line endings.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is a common pattern when implementing an offline cache with service workers.
[src:react-query/fetch-api-using-fetch] The service worker wants to return the response to the app, but also to cache the response.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:react-query/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
[src:react-query/state-management] This is especially the case when the state of any particular message or form on the page depends on factors outside of the current page, or available throughout several pages.
[src:react-query/state-management] For example, consider a user who is logged in and sees the 'welcome' message on their first visit to any page, but not on subsequent page visits.
[src:react-query/state-management] Does each page manage the state of the user being logged in?
[src:react-query/state-management] That would create too much copy pasting and duplication of code.
[src:react-query/state-management] Instead, you can use a state management pattern for handling messages (this may also include handling error messages and informative messages, along with the described welcome message) and then call this to receive a message as it becomes available.
[src:react-query/state-management] Examples of state management libraries include Pinia as a state management library for the Vue.js JavaScript framework.
[src:react-query/state-management] For the Angular framework there exist multiple community options: NgRx (based on Redux, with a lightweight alternative using Signals), NGXS and RxAngular.
[src:react-query/state-management] Redux is a general-purpose state management library that can be used with any of the above frameworks or other view libraries, but is very commonly used with the React library.
[src:react-query/state-management] As the documentation in Redux alludes, many of these state management libraries are lightweight and can be replaced by each other.
[src:react-query/state-management] It's also possible to roll your own based on a publish–subscribe pattern where your interface components (like form fields, buttons, and messages) listen to a centralized data store in your application for new changes.
